<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
<a class="spoiler" href="/questions/1312507-was-this-book-pro-stoicism-or-mocking-it">This question contains spoilers...</a>
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Was this book pro-stoicism or mocking it? While reading I interpreted it positively, but after finishing I kept thinking about Croker's weird speech, Conrad's Zeus references, and Croker's preaching tour. It's occurred to me that Tom Wolfe was mocking Stoicism. Is that the case? Were these references in there to make stoics sound a little crazy? <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_1312507'><a id="like_count_community_question_1312507" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/1312507?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">1 like</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F86172.A_Man_in_Full">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/1312507-was-this-book-pro-stoicism-or-mocking-it">3 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/1312507-was-this-book-pro-stoicism-or-mocking-it">Add your answer</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/15916140-devyn-duffy"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1618529547i/15916140._UY100_CR16,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/15916140-devyn-duffy">Devyn Duffy</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">A good question, although I&apos;m not sure why Wolfe would have bothered to include so much word-for-word discussion of Stoicism only to mock it, since no<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">A good question, although I'm not sure why Wolfe would have bothered to include so much word-for-word discussion of Stoicism only to mock it, since no one really talked much about Stoicism in the late '90s. Maybe he was satirizing the way he thought that people might respond to Stoicism, as if it were an unfamiliar religion. And while Conrad's thinking about Zeus seemed odd to me, in hindsight it was kind of refreshing that someone discovering Stoicism from a book would come up with his own interpretations that may be a little... idiosyncratic.<br /><br />Given that the hundreds of pages of plot resolve themselves with a short application of Stoicism, I suspect that Wolfe really was trying to make a pro-Stoic statement, as if to suggest that Stoicism could solve your complicated real-life problems easily.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

<div class='flagAnswer'>
<a class="right flag" rel="nofollow" id="flag_link1088058" title="Flag this answer as inappropriate." href="/flagged/new?resource_id=1088058&amp;resource_type=CommunityAnswer&amp;return_url=%2Fquestions%2F1312507-was-this-book-pro-stoicism-or-mocking-it%2Fanswers%2F1088058-a-good-question">flag</a>
</div>
