<div id="bookReviews">
  




  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section firstReview">
      

<div id="review_140177842" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/140177842" />
    <a title="Steve Lowe" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3268309-steve-lowe"><img alt="Steve Lowe" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1427727266p2/3268309.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/140177842?book_show_action=true">Jan 12, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steve Lowe" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steve Lowe" href="/user/show/3268309-steve-lowe">Steve Lowe</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer140177842" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6475875110759935304">Dear Tom Wolfe,<br/><br/>I am writing to you now about your insistence on describing what every character is wearing in every scene of your 741-page epic, <i>A Man in Full</i>. I am convinced that, had you chosen to avoid doing such a thing as describe each cut of cloth, each brand name, each sartorial style, and its significance based on the character or the setting, etc., this book could have been a much crisper, much leaner, much more <i>manly</i> 400 pages.<br/><br/>Sincerely, Steve<br/><br/>But I guess that’s what you get when a fopp</span>
  <span id="freeText6475875110759935304" style="display:none">Dear Tom Wolfe,<br><br>I am writing to you now about your insistence on describing what every character is wearing in every scene of your 741-page epic, <i>A Man in Full</i>. I am convinced that, had you chosen to avoid doing such a thing as describe each cut of cloth, each brand name, each sartorial style, and its significance based on the character or the setting, etc., this book could have been a much crisper, much leaner, much more <i>manly</i> 400 pages.<br><br>Sincerely, Steve<br><br>But I guess that’s what you get when a foppish little dandy such as this:<br><br><span>[image error]</span><br><br>… writes a book about what it is to be a man, or at least a portrait, or cross section if you will, of the state of manhood in the late 1990s south (Atlanta to be specific).<br><br>Let me say it this way: I don’t give a flying fuck what kind of suit your character is wearing from day to day. Maybe if it has some significance whatsoever to the plot, then that’s OK. But when you pull the reader aside so you can point out that a lawyer about to face a clamoring mob of reporters was afraid, and “not even his flawless sartorial armor – a new hard-finished worsted navy suit from Gus Carroll, a high-necked tab-collar shirt, a pale-blue crepe de chine necktie with a <i>perfect</i> dimple – could make him feel secure…” well, then I say, fuck you. I DON’T CARE! I’m guessing that’s what Tom Wolfe was wearing when he wrote that scene. In fact, by the looks of the guy, I’m guessing he changed his clothes every time he changed characters.<br><br>The characters, by the way, are the strength of this book, if you’re wondering. If you look past the convenient plot turns and less than surprising twists, the reliance on coincidence, and the fairly stereotypical and rudimentary categories of men (nearly every white man over 40 was either half bald or had “buttery jowls”, and quite often both), once Tommy Boy really gets into the character, he really gets in. Each character has a distinct voice, which is impressive since we follow along fairly closely with Charlie Croker (old, white, racisty real estate developer who’s about to lose everything), Roger (Too) White II (light-skinned African American lawyer who is almost “too white”), Conrad Hensley (the heart and soul of the book, a young man who loses everything after he’s laid off from one of Croker’s food warehouses), Martha Croker (Charlie’s first wife, who battles with her relevance in Atlanta’s social scene after being cast away by Charlie), and Raymond Peepgass (middle-aged loser who works at the bank going after Charlie and trying to be more than a meek little fish in a big pond).<br><br>Now, if Tommy Boy could have just gotten over his hang up with clothes, I would have liked this one so much better. If you like to dress fancy and spend all of your royalties on clothes, that’s fine. But don’t go mucking up what was otherwise a fine, well-written, engrossing novel with all of that bullshit. That cost you a star, Tom Wolfe. It cost you a star.<br><br>By the way, as I rapped out this review, I sat comfortably in my Faded Glory gray thermal long-sleeve tee (on clearance at Meijer, I think) and a pair of J. Crew pants that I got for free from the college kids who used to live across the street from us and were throwing out a bunch of clothes the day they moved out, and on to jobs in places like Knoxville and Cleveland, where they would no doubt be expected to wear clothing that was in some way worsted and lawyerly. In case you were wondering…<br></span>
  <a data-text-id="6475875110759935304" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


